# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sinatra-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:sinatra-deep/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] The code you changed will not take effect until you restart the server.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Please restart the server every time you change or use a code reloader like rerun or rack-unreloader.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is recommended to also run `gem install puma`, which Sinatra will pick up if available.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] In Sinatra, a route is an HTTP method paired with a URL-matching pattern.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Routes are matched in the order they are defined.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] The first route that matches the request is invoked.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] By the way, unless you disable the path traversal attack protection (see below), the request path might be modified before matching against your routes.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It looks like a condition, but it isn’t one!
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] These options will be merged into the global `:mustermann_opts` hash described below.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] `provides` searches the request’s Accept header.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] The return value of a route block determines at least the response body passed on to the HTTP client or at least the next middleware in the Rack stack.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Most commonly, this is a string, as in the above examples.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You can also use the `stream` helper method (described below) to reduce boilerplate and embed the streaming logic in the route.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] As shown above, Sinatra ships with built-in support for using String patterns and regular expressions as route matches.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Static files are served from the `./public` directory.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that the public directory name is not included in the URL.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] A file `./public/css/style.css` is made available as `http://example.com/css/style.css`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Use the `:static_cache_control` setting (see below) to add `Cache-Control` header info.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Each template language is exposed via its own rendering method.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This will render `views/index.erb` embedded in the `views/post.erb` (default is `views/layout.erb`, if it exists).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Options passed to the render method override options set via `set`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If it's a Symbol, specifies what template to use.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If you change this, instance variables and helper methods will not be available.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Template engine to use for rendering the layout.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Useful for languages that do not support layouts otherwise.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Defaults to the engine used for the template.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Special options only used for rendering the layout.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Templates are assumed to be located directly under the `./views` directory.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] One important thing to remember is that you always have to reference templates with symbols, even if they’re in a subdirectory (in this case, use: `:'subdir/template'` or `'subdir/template'.to_sym`).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You must use a symbol because otherwise rendering methods will render any strings passed to them directly.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Some languages have multiple implementations.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It also takes a block for inline templates (see example).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby methods (except for `yield`) from a Liquid template, you almost always want to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is not possible to call methods from Markdown, nor to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby from Markdown, you cannot use layouts written in Markdown.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] However, it is possible to use another rendering engine for the template than for the layout by passing the `:layout_engine` option.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is not possible to call methods from RDoc, nor to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby from RDoc, you cannot use layouts written in RDoc.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Since you cannot call Ruby methods directly from an AsciiDoc template, you almost always want to pass locals to it.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Templates are evaluated within the same context as route handlers.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This is typically used when rendering templates as partials from within other templates.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] A layout is usually just a template that calls `yield`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This code is mostly equivalent to `erb :index, :layout => :post`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Currently, the following rendering methods accept a block: `erb`, `haml`, `liquid`, `slim`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Also, the general `render` method accepts a block.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] NOTE: Inline templates defined in the source file that requires Sinatra are automatically loaded.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Call `enable :inline_templates` explicitly if you have inline templates in other source files.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If a template named “layout” exists, it will be used each time a template is rendered.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] To associate a file extension with a template engine, use `Tilt.register`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Before filters are evaluated before each request within the same context as the routes will be and can modify the request and response.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] After filters are evaluated after each request within the same context as the routes will be and can also modify the request and response.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note: Unless you use the `body` method rather than just returning a String from the routes, the body will not yet be available in the after filter, since it is generated later on.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] The effect is the same as including the modules in the application class.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] A session is used to keep state during requests.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] To improve security, the session data in the cookie is signed with a session secret using `HMAC-SHA1`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This session secret should optimally be a cryptographically secure random value of an appropriate length which for `HMAC-SHA1` is greater than or equal to 64 bytes (512 bits, 128 hex characters).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You would be advised not to use a secret that is less than 32 bytes of randomness (256 bits, 64 hex characters).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is therefore **very important** that you don’t just make the secret up, but instead use a secure random number generator to create it.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Humans are extremely bad at generating random values.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] By default, a 32 byte secure random session secret is generated for you by Sinatra, but it will change with every restart of your application.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If you have multiple instances of your application, and you let Sinatra generate the key, each instance would then have a different session key which is probably not what you want.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] For better security and usability it’s recommended that you generate a secure random secret and store it in an environment variable on each host running your application so that all of your application instances will share the same secret.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You should periodically rotate this session secret to a new value.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Set a `SESSION_SECRET` environment variable for Sinatra to the value you generated.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Make this value persistent across reboots of your host.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that `enable :sessions` actually stores all data in a cookie.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This might not always be what you want (storing lots of data will increase your traffic, for instance).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Another option is to **not** call `enable :sessions`, but instead pull in your middleware of choice as you would any other middleware.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is important to note that when using this method, session based protection **will not be enabled by default**.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] See ‘Configuring attack protection’ for more information.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] The route block is immediately exited and control continues with the next matching route.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If no matching route is found, a 404 is returned.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sometimes `pass` is not what you want, instead, you would like to get the result of calling another route.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that in the example above, you would ease testing and increase performance by simply moving `"bar"` into a helper used by both `/foo` and `/bar`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If you want the request to be sent to the same application instance rather than a duplicate, use `call!` instead of `call`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Check out the Rack specification if you want to learn more about `call`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is possible and recommended to set the status code and response body with the return value of the route block.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] However, in some scenarios, you might want to set the body at an arbitrary point in the execution flow.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You can do so with the `body` helper method.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It is also possible to pass a block to `body`, which will be executed by the Rack handler (this can be used to implement streaming, see “Return Values”).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Like `body`, `headers` and `status` with no arguments can be used to access their current values.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sometimes you want to start sending out data while still generating parts of the response body.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] In extreme examples, you want to keep sending data until the client closes the connection.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This allows you to implement streaming APIs, Server Sent Events, and can be used as the basis for WebSockets.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It can also be used to increase throughput if some but not all content depends on a slow resource.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that the streaming behavior, especially the number of concurrent requests, highly depends on the webserver used to serve the application.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Some servers might not even support streaming at all.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If the server does not support streaming, the body will be sent all at once after the block passed to `stream` finishes executing.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Streaming does not work at all with Shotgun.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If the optional parameter is set to `keep_open`, it will not call `close` on the stream object, allowing you to close it at any later point in the execution flow.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It’s also possible for the client to close the connection when trying to write to the socket.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Because of this, it’s recommended to check `out.closed?` before trying to write.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This logger will automatically take your Rack handler’s logging settings into account.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If logging is disabled, this method will return a dummy object, so you do not have to worry about it in your routes and filters.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] To avoid any logging middleware to be set up, set the `logging` option to `nil`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] However, keep in mind that `logger` will in that case return `nil`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] A common use case is when you want to set your own logger.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sinatra will use whatever it will find in `env['rack.logger']`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] When using `send_file` or static files you may have mime types Sinatra doesn’t understand.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] It takes reverse proxies and Rack routers into account - if present.
