[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Setting your headers correctly is the foundation for proper HTTP caching.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] To properly use caches, you should consider using `etag` or `last_modified`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] These helpers will not do any caching for you, but rather feed the necessary information to your cache.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Use the `:static_cache_control` setting (see below) to add `Cache-Control` header info to static files.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] According to RFC 2616, your application should behave differently if the If-Match or If-None-Match header is set to `*`, depending on whether the resource requested is already in existence.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sinatra assumes resources for safe (like get) and idempotent (like put) requests are already in existence, whereas other resources (for instance post requests) are treated as new resources.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] File name to be used in the response, defaults to the real file name.
