[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sinatra offers a `time_for` helper method that generates a Time object from the given value.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This method is used internally by `expires`, `last_modified` and akin.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] But it is useful that you can actually override this method to hook in your own lookup mechanism.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You can also easily wrap this up in an extension and share it with others!
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that `find_template` does not check if the file really exists but rather calls the given block for all possible paths.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] This is not a performance issue, since `render` will use `break` as soon as a file is found.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Also, template locations (and content) will be cached if you are not running in development mode.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] You should keep that in mind if you write a really crazy method.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sinatra is using Rack::Protection to defend your application against common, opportunistic attacks.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] By default, Sinatra will only set up session based protection if `:sessions` have been enabled.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Sometimes you may want to set up sessions “outside” of the Sinatra app, such as in the config.ru or with a separate `Rack::Builder` instance.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If disabled, Sinatra will allow relative redirects, however, Sinatra will no longer conform with RFC 2616 (HTTP 1.1), which only allows absolute redirects.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Enable if your app is running behind a reverse proxy that has not been set up properly.
