[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Whether or not to enable web attack protections.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Path to the folder public files are served from.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Disables logs generated by Sinatra's start and stop commands.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Whether or not to reload templates between requests.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Raise unhandled errors (will stop application).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Any explicitly defined error handlers always override this setting.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] If enabled, Sinatra will handle starting the web server.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Do not enable if using rackup or other means.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Server or list of servers to use for built-in server.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Order indicates priority, default depends on Ruby implementation.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] See 'Using Sessions' section for more information.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Show a stack trace in the browser when an exception happens.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] to trigger app-specified error handling before showing a stack trace in the browser.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Whether Sinatra should handle serving static files.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Disable when using a server able to do this on its own.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Enabled by default in classic style, disabled for modular apps.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Whether Sinatra should handle system signals.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Whether or not to set the X-Cascade header if no route matches.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] There are 2 lifecycle events currently exposed by Sinatra.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] One when the server starts and one when it stops.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Note that these callbacks only work when using Sinatra to start the web server.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] There are three predefined `environments`: `"development"`, `"production"` and `"test"`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] Environments can be set through the `APP_ENV` environment variable.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] In the `"development"` environment all templates are reloaded between requests, and special `not_found` and `error` handlers display stack traces in your browser.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p01] In the `"production"` and `"test"` environments, templates are cached by default.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Error handlers run within the same context as routes and before filters, which means you get all the goodies it has to offer, like `haml`, `erb`, `halt`, etc.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The `error` handler is invoked any time an exception is raised from a route block or a filter.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra installs special `not_found` and `error` handlers when running under the development environment to display nice stack traces and additional debugging information in your browser.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] When `raise_errors` option is `true`, errors that are unhandled are raised outside of the application.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Additionally, any errors that would have been caught by the catch-all error handler are raised.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] In the `test` environment, `raise_errors` is set to `true` by default.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] This means that in order to write a test for a catch-all error handler, `raise_errors` must temporarily be set to `false` for that particular test.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra rides on Rack, a minimal standard interface for Ruby web frameworks.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] One of Rack’s most interesting capabilities for application developers is support for “middleware” – components that sit between the server and your application monitoring and/or manipulating the HTTP request/response to provide various types of common functionality.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The semantics of `use` are identical to those defined for the Rack::Builder DSL (most frequently used from rackup files).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Rack is distributed with a variety of standard middleware for logging, debugging, URL routing, authentication, and session handling.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra uses many of these components automatically based on configuration so you typically don’t have to `use` them explicitly.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] You can find useful middleware in rack, rack-contrib, or in the Rack wiki.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra tests can be written using any Rack-based testing library or framework.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Note: If you are using Sinatra in the modular style, replace `Sinatra::Application` above with the class name of your app.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Defining your app at the top-level works well for micro-apps but has considerable drawbacks when building reusable components such as Rack middleware, Rails metal, simple libraries with a server component, or even Sinatra extensions.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The top-level assumes a micro-app style configuration (e.g., a single application file, `./public` and `./views` directories, logging, exception detail page, etc.).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The methods available to `Sinatra::Base` subclasses are exactly the same as those available via the top-level DSL.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Most options are disabled by default, including the built-in server.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] See Configuring Settings for details on available options and their behavior.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Contrary to common belief, there is nothing wrong with the classic style.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] If it suits your application, you do not have to switch to a modular application.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The main disadvantage of using the classic style rather than the modular style is that you will only have one Sinatra application per Ruby process.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] If you plan to use more than one, switch to the modular style.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] There is no reason you cannot mix the modular and classic styles.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Not only is Sinatra able to use other Rack middleware, any Sinatra application can, in turn, be added in front of any Rack endpoint as middleware itself.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sometimes you want to create new applications at runtime without having to assign them to a constant.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] This is especially useful for testing Sinatra extensions or using Sinatra in your own library.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The scope you are currently in determines what methods and variables are available.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Every Sinatra application corresponds to a subclass of `Sinatra::Base`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] If you are using the top-level DSL (`require 'sinatra'`), then this class is `Sinatra::Application`, otherwise it is the subclass you created explicitly.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] At the class level, you have methods like `get` or `before`, but you cannot access the `request` or `session` objects, as there is only a single application class for all requests.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] For every incoming request, a new instance of your application class is created, and all handler blocks run in that scope.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] From within this scope you can access the `request` and `session` objects or call rendering methods like `erb` or `haml`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The delegation scope just forwards methods to the class scope.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] However, it does not behave exactly like the class scope, as you do not have the class binding.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Only methods explicitly marked for delegation are available, and you do not share variables/state with the class scope (read: you have a different `self`).
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] You can explicitly add method delegations by calling `Sinatra::Delegator.delegate :method_name`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Have a look at the code for yourself: here’s the Sinatra::Delegator mixin being extending the main object.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra doesn’t impose any concurrency model but leaves that to the underlying Rack handler (server) like Puma or Falcon.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra itself is thread-safe, so there won’t be any problem if the Rack handler uses a threaded model of concurrency.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The latest stable release of TruffleRuby is supported.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] The latest stable release of JRuby is supported.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] It is not recommended to use C extensions with JRuby.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Versions of Ruby before 2.7.8 are no longer supported as of Sinatra 4.0.0.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra should work on any operating system supported by the chosen Ruby implementation.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Running Sinatra on a not officially supported Ruby flavor means that if things only break there we assume it’s not our issue but theirs.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] If you would like to use Sinatra’s latest bleeding-edge code, feel free to run your application against the main branch, it should be rather stable.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] If you want to run your application with the latest Sinatra, using Bundler is the recommended way.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Note that you will have to list all your application’s dependencies in the `Gemfile`.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra’s direct dependencies (Rack and Tilt) will, however, be automatically fetched and added by Bundler.
[src:sinatra-deep/intro-p02] Sinatra follows Semantic Versioning, both SemVer and SemVerTag.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Rack is used by many Ruby web frameworks and libraries, such as Ruby on Rails and Sinatra.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Many Ruby applications are called "rack-compliant".
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Rack has inspired similar frameworks in JavaScript (jack.js), Clojure, Perl (Plack), Common Lisp (Clack), and .NET (OWIN).
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The characteristics of a Rack application is that the application object responds to the call method.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The call method takes in the environment object as argument and returns the Rack response object.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] In case the application is being used as a middleware, the environment can have objects that would provide session information, logging capabilities, information on the size of the data that can be used for read and writes etc.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] In addition to these, the server can store their own data in the environment.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The rack server object returns a response which contains three parts: the status, headers and the body.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Rack::Response provides a convenient interface to create a Rack response.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The class Rack::Response is defined in lib/rack/response.rb.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] To use the Response class, instantiate it from the middleware layer down the stack.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Rack makes it easy to add a chain of middleware components between the application and the web server.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] Multiple middleware components can be used in the rack which modifies the request/response before handing it over to the next component.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The Rack server adds multiple middle middleware by default for the functionalities like showing exception with all the details, validating the request and responses according to the Rack spec etc.
[src:sinatra-deep/rack-web-server-interface] The server for the above code can be initiated using "rackup helloWorld.ru" and can be accessed at http://localhost:9292/ The default port used by the Rack application is 9292.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:sinatra-deep/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Designed and developed by Blake Mizerany, Sinatra is small and flexible.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] It does not follow the typical model–view–controller pattern used in other frameworks, such as Ruby on Rails.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Instead, Sinatra focuses on "quickly creating web-applications in Ruby with minimal effort." Because of much smaller size compared to Ruby on Rails, it is also called *microframework*.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Some notable companies and institutions that use Sinatra include Apple, BBC, the British Government's Government Digital Service, LinkedIn, the National Security Agency, Engine Yard, Heroku, GitHub, Stripe, and Songbird.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Travis CI provides much of the financial support for Sinatra's development.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Sinatra was created and open-sourced in 2007.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] It inspired multiple ports and similar projects in other programming languages, such as Express.js and Scalatra.
[src:sinatra-deep/sinatra-software] Mizerany and Heroku's Adam Wiggins introduced and discussed Sinatra at RubyConf 2008.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:sinatra-deep/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
